% ==========================================
% EXERCISE 4: PUBLIC EDUCATION EXPENDITURE (% OF GDP)
% ==========================================
\section{Exercise 4: Public Education Expenditure as \% of GDP}

\subsection{Overview}
This dataset contains annual public expenditure on education expressed as a
percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP). Unlike the previous datasets focused 
on student enrolments, this indicator reflects how much of a country's economic 
output is invested into its education system. Each row corresponds to a single 
country-year observation.

\subsection{Data Cleaning}
The raw dataset obtained from \texttt{data.un.org} required several preprocessing
steps to ensure consistency:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Filtering units:} Only entries where the unit was ``Percent'' were retained.
    \item \textbf{Removing unusable entries:} Missing values (``..'') and non-numeric entries 
    were dropped.
    \item \textbf{Non-country entries:} Regional aggregates such as ``Arab States'' and 
    ``Landlocked Developing Countries'' were removed.
    \item \textbf{Type conversion:} The \textit{observation\_value} column was converted 
    to numeric floating-point values.
    \item \textbf{Column consistency:} Column names were cleaned and standardized 
    (e.g., \textit{Reference Area} → \textit{reference\_area}).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Visualisation}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{ex4_exp_gni_trend.png}
    \caption{Ex 4: Global mean public education expenditure as \% of GDP over time.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{ex4_exp_gni_hist.png}
    \caption{Ex 4: Distribution of education expenditure as \% of GDP across all countries.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{ex4_exp_gni_top20.png}
    \caption{Ex 4: Top 20 countries by maximum education expenditure as \% of GDP.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Observations}
Several patterns emerge from the visual analysis:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Most countries allocate between \textbf{3\% and 7\%} of their GDP to education.
    \item Smaller or developing economies tend to show the highest relative expenditure.
    \item Global spending shows moderate variation across years, with no dramatic shifts.
    \item Large fluctuations in particular countries suggest political or economic instability.
\end{itemize}



\section{Conclusion}
The comprehensive analysis of Primary, Secondary, and Tertiary education reveals a clear narrative.
While Primary and Secondary education show a historical male dominance in enrolment numbers, 
\textbf{Tertiary education shows a reversal of this trend}, with female participation exceeding 
male participation in the most recent years of the dataset. 

Common data quality issues—specifically the lack of explicit male data and inconsistent 
units—were successfully mitigated through a unified Python preprocessing pipeline, allowing 
for accurate comparative analysis across all three education levels.

\end{document}


