% EXERCISE 5: PUBLIC EDUCATION EXPENDITURE (% OF total Government expenditure)
% ==========================================
\section{Exercise 45: Public Education Expenditure as \% of total government expenditure}

\subsection{Overview}
\documentclass[a4paper,12pt]{article}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{geometry}
\geometry{margin=1in}

\begin{document}

\title{Analysis of Public Expenditure on Education}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}


This dataset reports annual public expenditure on education as a percentage of total government expenditure. 
Like the last dataset, this indicator shows how much of a government’s budget is allocated to education each year. 
Each row is a country–year pair with one numeric value—observation_value—measured in percent, indicating the share of total public spending devoted to education. 
Supporting fields include reference_area (country), time_period (year), and metadata columns (sex, age_group) marked “Not applicable.”

\section{Methodology}

The original raw dataset was cleaned in several steps. 
Column names were standardised, 
missing values were removed 
and duplicate rows were dropped.


The variable of interest was:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \texttt{Observation\_Value}: Public Expenditure on Education (\% of Total Government Expenditure)
\end{itemize}

To explore a possible correlation between government expenditure and education,
the education expenditure data were merged with a separate cleaned dataset containing life expectancy
values for the same countries and years. Two main visualisations were created:

\begin{itemize}
    \item A line chart showing how education spending changed over time for a
          selection of countries.
    \item A scatter plot comparing education spending with life expectancy.
\end{itemize}

Simple descriptive statistics, such as mean expenditure per country, were also
computed.

\section{Results}

\subsection{Education Expenditure Over Time}

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{education_over_time.png}
\caption{Public Expenditure on Education (\% of Total Government Expenditure)
for Germany, India, the United States of America, and Brazil.}
\end{figure}

The time-series plot shows that education expenditure differs considerably across
countries. Germany and the United States show relatively stable spending over
time, while India and Brazil display more noticeable fluctuations. India has the
highest peak in education expenditure in the early 2000s, while Germany remains
closer to 10\% throughout the period.

\subsection{Education Spending vs Life Expectancy}

\begin{figure}[h!]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{education_vs_lifeexp.png}
\caption{Scatter plot of education spending (\% of GDP) vs.\ life expectancy for
a random sample of countries.}
\end{figure}

The scatter plot suggests a mild upward trend, meaning that countries spending a
higher share of their resources on education tend to have slightly higher life
expectancy. However, the points are spread out and not closely aligned, so the
relationship is not very strong. Some countries with similar education
expenditure levels show quite different life expectancy values.

\subsection{Average Education Expenditure by Country}

A simple mean comparison shows which countries spend the most on education as a
share of government expenditure. The highest values in the dataset include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Vanuatu (29.3\%)
    \item Lesotho (26.2\%)
    \item Tunisia (25.5\%)
    \item Yemen (24.4\%)
    \item Kenya (24.4\%)
\end{itemize}

These countries consistently allocate a relatively large share of their budgets
to education compared to others in the dataset.

\section{Observations}

Overall, the results show that education expenditure varies widely between
countries and across years. Some countries invest a stable proportion of their
government budget in education, while others show stronger fluctuations.

The scatter plot indicates a weak positive association between education
spending and life expectancy. Although this suggests that higher investment in
education may be linked to better social outcomes, the relationship is far from
clear, and many other factors likely influence life expectancy.

\section{Conclusion}

From this we can conclude that:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Education expenditure levels differ notably between countries.
    \item Some countries, such as India and Brazil, show strong year-to-year
          variation in spending.
    \item There is a slight positive relationship between education expenditure
          and life expectancy, based on visual inspection.
\end{itemize}

To obtain more precise conclusions, additional variables such as GDP, health
spending, or demographic factors would be needed.
analysis provides a basic overview of education spending patterns worldwide.

